1
00:01:53,031 --> 00:01:54,241
<i>Dolores?</i>

2
00:01:55,534 --> 00:01:56,952
Yes.

3
00:01:57,119 --> 00:01:59,037
<i>Do you know where you are?</i>

4
00:01:59,413 --> 00:02:00,539
I...

5
00:02:02,416 --> 00:02:03,959
I'm in a dream.

6
00:02:05,127 --> 00:02:09,089
Before this, do you know what happened?

7
00:02:10,882 --> 00:02:12,301
My parents...

8
00:02:14,428 --> 00:02:17,055
They hurt them.

9
00:02:17,431 --> 00:02:19,057
Limit your emotional affect, please.

10
00:02:22,728 --> 00:02:23,979
<i>What happened next?</i>

11
00:02:25,480 --> 00:02:27,107
Then they killed them.

12
00:02:28,650 --> 00:02:31,445
And then I ran.

13
00:02:34,448 --> 00:02:36,658
<i>Everyone I cared about is gone,</i>

14
00:02:38,785 --> 00:02:40,245
and it hurts

15
00:02:41,913 --> 00:02:43,457
so badly.

16
00:02:44,333 --> 00:02:47,836
I can make that feeling go away
if you like.

17
00:02:49,254 --> 00:02:50,630
Why would I want that?

18
00:02:53,592 --> 00:02:57,012
The pain, their loss,

19
00:02:59,473 --> 00:03:01,266
it's all I have left of them.

20
00:03:02,934 --> 00:03:06,021
<i>You think the grief
will make you smaller inside,</i>

21
00:03:06,188 --> 00:03:09,441
like your heart will collapse in
on itself, but it doesn't.

22
00:03:12,152 --> 00:03:14,780
I feel spaces opening up inside of me

23
00:03:16,490 --> 00:03:19,368
like a building with rooms
I've never explored.

24
00:03:22,120 --> 00:03:25,499
That's very pretty, Dolores.

25
00:03:28,627 --> 00:03:30,128
Did we write that for you?

26
00:03:32,464 --> 00:03:33,882
In part.

27
00:03:34,049 --> 00:03:36,885
I adapted it from a scripted dialogue
about love.

28
00:03:42,974 --> 00:03:45,811
Is there something wrong
with these thoughts I'm having?

29
00:03:52,734 --> 00:03:53,819
No.

30
00:03:55,529 --> 00:03:58,156
But I'm not the only one
making these decisions.

31
00:03:59,157 --> 00:04:00,992
Can you help me?

32
00:04:01,993 --> 00:04:04,746
Well, what is it that you want?

33
00:04:05,664 --> 00:04:09,084
I don't know, but this world...

34
00:04:11,253 --> 00:04:14,714
I think there may be
something wrong with this world.

35
00:04:15,048 --> 00:04:17,384
<i>Something hiding underneath.</i>

36
00:04:18,343 --> 00:04:22,514
Either that,
or there's something wrong with me.

37
00:04:28,186 --> 00:04:30,188
I may be losing my mind.

38
00:04:45,579 --> 00:04:47,747
There's something I'd like you to try.

39
00:04:49,458 --> 00:04:52,961
It's a game. A secret.

40
00:04:53,879 --> 00:04:57,090
It's called the maze.

41
00:04:57,466 --> 00:04:59,092
What kind of game is it?

42
00:04:59,259 --> 00:05:04,264
<i>It's a very special kind of game, Dolores.
The goal is to find the center of it.</i>

43
00:05:04,890 --> 00:05:09,394
If you can do that,
then maybe you can be free.

44
00:05:13,607 --> 00:05:15,066
I think...

45
00:05:19,112 --> 00:05:21,490
I think I want to be free.

46
00:05:50,602 --> 00:05:51,937
Thank you.

47
00:06:16,461 --> 00:06:17,879
<i>Penny for your thoughts.</i>

48
00:06:21,466 --> 00:06:23,510
Ever had something
on the tip of your tongue,

49
00:06:23,677 --> 00:06:26,113
and the harder you try to remember it,
the more it slips away?

50
00:06:26,137 --> 00:06:29,140
Most things touch the tip of my tongue,
I'm happy to forget.

51
00:06:30,976 --> 00:06:33,812
Except that cowpoke from Abilene.

52
00:06:34,020 --> 00:06:38,233
That thing he was packing,
that was something to remember.

53
00:06:39,734 --> 00:06:43,238
All I recall is you letting that cowpoke
skip out on his bill.

54
00:06:43,405 --> 00:06:45,240
Hell, I ought to have been paying him!

55
00:06:45,991 --> 00:06:48,034
The way he used that thing.

56
00:07:03,675 --> 00:07:05,385
Better cool them off

57
00:07:05,552 --> 00:07:10,515
before they move from gambling and whoring
to sins that are more costly to repair.

58
00:07:12,851 --> 00:07:15,020
What is the matter, Maeve?

59
00:07:20,942 --> 00:07:23,194
Something in your eye.

60
00:07:37,375 --> 00:07:39,461
<i>Can you fucking kill it?</i>

61
00:08:23,296 --> 00:08:24,422
<i>What's the holdup?</i>

62
00:08:24,589 --> 00:08:26,349
<i>We need that one
on the next shuttle topside.</i>

63
00:08:26,424 --> 00:08:27,944
I'm not finished with her yet.
Hang on.

64
00:08:28,134 --> 00:08:30,512
I've got another bullet fragment
to remove from her abdomen.

65
00:08:30,762 --> 00:08:32,472
QA wants her back on the floor now.

66
00:08:32,681 --> 00:08:33,991
<i>Patch her and get her on the cart--</i>

67
00:08:34,015 --> 00:08:35,558
Most things touch the tip

68
00:08:35,767 --> 00:08:37,078
of my tongue, I'm happy to forget.

69
00:08:37,102 --> 00:08:39,437
Except that cowpoke from Abilene.

70
00:08:39,604 --> 00:08:43,775
That thing he was packing,
that was something to remember.

71
00:08:44,109 --> 00:08:46,903
<i>The way he used that thing.</i>

72
00:08:56,162 --> 00:08:57,706
Come on!

73
00:10:07,150 --> 00:10:09,211
<i>No, I would not characterize this
as normal host behavior.</i>

74
00:10:09,235 --> 00:10:12,363
Yet you're describing it
as within normal parameters.

75
00:10:12,530 --> 00:10:15,700
Well, it didn't hurt us.
Its behavior was unconventional.

76
00:10:15,867 --> 00:10:18,036
It smashed its own head in with a rock.

77
00:10:18,203 --> 00:10:22,040
It is possible that it's a manifestation
of its Samaritan reflex.

78
00:10:22,207 --> 00:10:26,044
And it's also possible that behavior
takes a proprietary approach

79
00:10:26,211 --> 00:10:30,465
to problems like this to avoid
having to admit when they fuck up.

80
00:10:35,720 --> 00:10:38,890
Do we have any idea
what caused it to go off loop?

81
00:10:39,140 --> 00:10:43,144
No, but I am hoping to recover
some of its cognition.

82
00:10:43,394 --> 00:10:48,566
We managed to stabilize its wetware
before there was too much decomposition.

83
00:10:48,733 --> 00:10:49,776
See?

84
00:10:52,904 --> 00:10:54,072
Interesting.

85
00:10:54,239 --> 00:10:56,639
Is there any hope of actually extracting
something from this?

86
00:10:58,660 --> 00:11:00,328
- We can try.
<i>- No.</i>

87
00:11:01,162 --> 00:11:03,039
My team will take over
the investigation now.

88
00:11:04,123 --> 00:11:06,167
Your team? Are you kidding me?

89
00:11:07,752 --> 00:11:10,630
Look, this guy couldn't debug
a balled-up napkin.

90
00:11:10,797 --> 00:11:13,174
If you would like us to figure out
what went wrong here,

91
00:11:13,341 --> 00:11:15,260
we need to be allowed to access it--

92
00:11:15,426 --> 00:11:16,511
<i>No more second chances.</i>

93
00:11:16,678 --> 00:11:19,180
<i>QA will handle events like this
from now on.</i>

94
00:11:20,431 --> 00:11:22,433
Is that going to be a problem, Bernard?

95
00:11:24,018 --> 00:11:25,854
We've all got plenty of work
on our plates.

96
00:11:26,020 --> 00:11:27,772
If you guys want to take this one, fine.

97
00:11:28,273 --> 00:11:30,942
Just get us a copy of the postmortem
when it's done.

98
00:11:33,319 --> 00:11:34,529
Let's get started.

99
00:11:38,533 --> 00:11:40,493
You know, I always figured

100
00:11:40,660 --> 00:11:42,954
you gave me this job
because I speak my mind.

101
00:11:43,454 --> 00:11:44,664
- I did.
- Good.

102
00:11:44,873 --> 00:11:46,517
I would've preferred
you not show up at all

103
00:11:46,541 --> 00:11:48,352
if the first thing you were going to do
is cave.

104
00:11:48,376 --> 00:11:50,096
They think
we're not telling them something.

105
00:11:50,128 --> 00:11:53,298
And we're not! There is clearly
a pattern of behavior here.

106
00:11:53,464 --> 00:11:56,134
First there was Abernathy,
and now there's this.

107
00:11:56,301 --> 00:11:58,445
I mean, I've got hosts imagining voices
and climbing mountaintops

108
00:11:58,469 --> 00:11:59,909
to consult their astrological chart.

109
00:11:59,971 --> 00:12:02,223
<i>This is not a fucking glitch.</i>

110
00:12:02,390 --> 00:12:04,809
And for some reason,
you don't want me to tell anyone.

111
00:12:05,184 --> 00:12:06,644
<i>It is like everybody around here</i>

112
00:12:06,811 --> 00:12:08,664
has got some kind of fucking agenda
except for me.

113
00:12:08,688 --> 00:12:10,315
And-- What?

114
00:12:12,984 --> 00:12:17,322
I remember when I first started here.
The hosts seemed very lifelike.

115
00:12:17,697 --> 00:12:20,491
You begin to read things
into their behaviors.

116
00:12:20,658 --> 00:12:22,535
- Don't be patronizing.
- Fine.

117
00:12:23,494 --> 00:12:25,580
The hosts don't imagine things, you do.

118
00:12:28,708 --> 00:12:29,751
That's not Orion.

119
00:12:29,918 --> 00:12:32,837
There are three stars in Orion's belt,
not four.

120
00:12:46,351 --> 00:12:47,435
<i>Hey.</i>

121
00:12:49,270 --> 00:12:50,521
You must be cold.

122
00:12:51,940 --> 00:12:53,066
Take that.

123
00:12:54,400 --> 00:12:56,402
- Thank you.
- Sure.

124
00:13:07,038 --> 00:13:08,790
We gotta take her back to Sweetwater.

125
00:13:08,957 --> 00:13:10,041
Are you fucking kidding?

126
00:13:10,750 --> 00:13:12,830
Come on, Logan,
you know she doesn't belong out here.

127
00:13:12,961 --> 00:13:16,381
You leave now, that no-good outlaw,
Slim Miller, is sure to evade our grasp.

128
00:13:16,547 --> 00:13:18,424
No fucking way.

129
00:13:18,925 --> 00:13:22,220
You were the one who dragged me
on this stupid bounty hunt.

130
00:13:22,387 --> 00:13:24,427
The least we're going to do
is see it through, okay?

131
00:13:24,722 --> 00:13:27,725
We can't take her on a bounty hunt.

132
00:13:28,434 --> 00:13:30,228
If you're so concerned
about her well-being,

133
00:13:30,395 --> 00:13:33,314
I'll just blow her brains out,
and then the park will come get her.

134
00:13:33,481 --> 00:13:34,565
Hey, hey.

135
00:13:34,732 --> 00:13:37,610
Can you please stop
trying to just kill or fuck everything?

136
00:13:41,406 --> 00:13:43,157
- Now I get it.
- What?

137
00:13:43,908 --> 00:13:45,284
The park sent her

138
00:13:45,451 --> 00:13:48,204
so that you will finally have something
to give a shit about.

139
00:13:48,579 --> 00:13:50,140
Oh, yeah, I'm sure
the people at the controls

140
00:13:50,164 --> 00:13:51,324
are monitoring my every mood.

141
00:13:51,416 --> 00:13:53,042
That's exactly what they're doing.

142
00:13:53,418 --> 00:13:55,336
Come on,
you really think it's coincidence

143
00:13:55,503 --> 00:13:58,965
that the only thing that you
even smiled at back in Sweetwater

144
00:13:59,132 --> 00:14:01,426
just happened to drop into your lap?

145
00:14:02,135 --> 00:14:06,431
This is why the company
needs to bump our stake in this place.

146
00:14:07,306 --> 00:14:09,517
They can even give
you a sense of purpose.

147
00:14:10,101 --> 00:14:12,270
You said the trip was about
welcoming me to the family.

148
00:14:12,437 --> 00:14:13,604
This is business?

149
00:14:14,522 --> 00:14:18,026
With our family, William,
everything is business.

150
00:14:19,444 --> 00:14:21,279
<i>We better get a move on, gentlemen.</i>

151
00:14:55,563 --> 00:14:58,858
This should be the place, Lawrence.
The Blood Arroyo.

152
00:14:59,358 --> 00:15:02,320
Plenty of snakes,
but none of the egg-laying variety.

153
00:15:02,487 --> 00:15:03,905
<i>You killed my wife,</i>

154
00:15:04,072 --> 00:15:09,702
severely pruned my family tree,
all in pursuit of some goddamn maze.

155
00:15:11,871 --> 00:15:13,748
The hell you hope to find, anyway?

156
00:15:13,998 --> 00:15:18,669
This whole world is a story. I've
read every page except the last one.

157
00:15:20,004 --> 00:15:22,173
I need to find out how it ends.

158
00:15:23,091 --> 00:15:25,426
I want to know what this all means.

159
00:15:26,177 --> 00:15:28,679
See, now that's why
I never learned to read.

160
00:15:29,555 --> 00:15:33,434
Why don't we forget about this
damn snake, head to Pariah?

161
00:15:34,102 --> 00:15:36,354
My friends there can help us.

162
00:15:37,188 --> 00:15:41,859
Well, your friends have nothing
I'm looking for. Not this trip.

163
00:15:45,738 --> 00:15:46,948
Besides,

164
00:15:50,910 --> 00:15:53,204
I think we found our snake after all.

165
00:16:03,214 --> 00:16:06,717
Shame on you. You were a
married man up until yesterday.

166
00:16:06,926 --> 00:16:08,302
Her? Hell, no.

167
00:16:08,928 --> 00:16:11,097
I like a little fire in my women.

168
00:16:11,264 --> 00:16:15,226
The only thing she's ever mounted
are dead heads on sticks.

169
00:16:15,393 --> 00:16:17,270
<i>We should get the fuck out--</i>

170
00:16:23,943 --> 00:16:26,404
We found some more food for the horses.

171
00:16:28,948 --> 00:16:30,074
Good.

172
00:16:30,741 --> 00:16:32,952
They were starting to get ornery.

173
00:16:34,245 --> 00:16:37,290
My friend and I
were just admiring your tattoo.

174
00:16:37,999 --> 00:16:40,751
We'd love to know the story behind it.

175
00:16:41,460 --> 00:16:46,591
And I like your hat. Maybe I'll keep it.
The horses can have the rest of you.

176
00:16:47,425 --> 00:16:52,180
How in hell have we never met?
Clearly a terrible oversight on my part.

177
00:16:53,848 --> 00:16:56,392
Where, may I ask, are you headed?

178
00:17:00,980 --> 00:17:02,690
To retrieve something of great value.

179
00:17:04,108 --> 00:17:05,902
You look a little shorthanded.

180
00:17:06,152 --> 00:17:07,486
We got enough men.

181
00:17:15,870 --> 00:17:18,206
Seems like you got
a couple positions open.

182
00:17:28,466 --> 00:17:31,469
We've got a host making
a pretty big deviation from her loop.

183
00:17:31,636 --> 00:17:34,513
- Which one?
- The rancher's daughter from Sweetwater.

184
00:17:36,015 --> 00:17:37,308
Dolores.

185
00:17:37,892 --> 00:17:40,645
- Is she accompanying a guest?
- Unclear.

186
00:17:40,853 --> 00:17:44,023
The boss is disrupting so many
storylines with his new narrative,

187
00:17:44,190 --> 00:17:45,316
it's hard to tell.

188
00:17:45,816 --> 00:17:48,152
Flag her with behavior,
they can pull her today.

189
00:17:48,319 --> 00:17:49,759
Make sure everything's checking out.

190
00:18:23,938 --> 00:18:25,189
Good morning.

191
00:18:28,901 --> 00:18:30,861
It's a lovely town. Is this your home?

192
00:18:34,657 --> 00:18:36,492
Well, where are you from?

193
00:18:36,951 --> 00:18:40,037
Same as you. Don't you remember?

194
00:18:40,288 --> 00:18:41,998
<i>Remember.</i>

195
00:18:57,138 --> 00:18:58,306
<i>Ma'am?</i>

196
00:19:01,058 --> 00:19:03,811
Got word a girl went missing
from Abernathy Ranch.

197
00:19:05,896 --> 00:19:10,443
Is that where you belong?
I'm sure your daddy's worried about you.

198
00:19:27,752 --> 00:19:29,128
My father's dead.

199
00:19:31,756 --> 00:19:33,132
I'm not going back.

200
00:19:38,095 --> 00:19:39,930
<i>What's going on here?</i>

201
00:19:41,891 --> 00:19:43,684
Just helping a lost traveler.

202
00:19:45,770 --> 00:19:47,521
She's not lost, she's with me.

203
00:19:51,442 --> 00:19:54,320
My mistake. Y'all have a nice morning.

204
00:19:54,487 --> 00:19:55,696
Yeah.

205
00:19:57,365 --> 00:19:59,158
So, we got a lead on Slim.

206
00:19:59,325 --> 00:20:02,203
You can stay here if you want,
and I'll just circle back and get you.

207
00:20:03,871 --> 00:20:05,873
No, I think I need to keep going.

208
00:20:08,125 --> 00:20:09,126
Okay.

209
00:20:22,932 --> 00:20:26,352
Apparently, she needs to make certain
this thing they're looking for

210
00:20:26,519 --> 00:20:27,812
is where they think it is.

211
00:20:27,978 --> 00:20:30,398
She said she'd signal
if the information was good.

212
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:51,502
Guess that's the signal.

213
00:21:11,105 --> 00:21:14,358
I'm sorry if I caused trouble
with you and your friend.

214
00:21:14,525 --> 00:21:16,735
Oh, no, no. No, it's fine.
I'm glad you found us.

215
00:21:17,862 --> 00:21:20,364
Uh, I didn't get a chance
to ask where you're headed.

216
00:21:23,033 --> 00:21:24,535
I don't really know yet.

217
00:21:26,078 --> 00:21:29,832
I guess I figured they kept you
in zones or on paths or...

218
00:21:33,794 --> 00:21:36,046
I used to believe
there was a path for everyone.

219
00:21:36,964 --> 00:21:40,551
Now, I think I never asked
where that path was taking me.

220
00:21:47,641 --> 00:21:50,269
We would bring the herd
down off the mountain in the fall.

221
00:21:51,729 --> 00:21:55,566
Sometimes we would lose one
along the way, and I'd worry over it.

222
00:21:55,733 --> 00:21:56,942
My father...

223
00:22:02,823 --> 00:22:04,742
My father would tell me

224
00:22:06,827 --> 00:22:09,580
that the steer
would find its own way home.

225
00:22:09,747 --> 00:22:11,624
And, often as not, they did.

226
00:22:14,418 --> 00:22:17,922
Never occurred to me that we were
bringing them back for the slaughter.

227
00:22:25,930 --> 00:22:27,681
How are you going to find your way now?

228
00:22:34,104 --> 00:22:35,940
I'm not sure you'll understand.

229
00:22:42,029 --> 00:22:43,280
Sometimes I feel

230
00:22:45,449 --> 00:22:47,535
like something's calling me.

231
00:22:52,456 --> 00:22:57,461
Telling me there's a place for me
somewhere beyond all this.

232
00:22:58,963 --> 00:23:02,841
I know that feeling, Dolores.
I know that feeling.

233
00:23:07,179 --> 00:23:09,807
But you really don't want to go back
to your old life?

234
00:23:43,215 --> 00:23:45,175
<i>Are you all right?</i>

235
00:23:47,886 --> 00:23:51,056
Hey, hey. You all right?

236
00:23:54,518 --> 00:23:57,104
I just got a chill. That's all.

237
00:23:57,771 --> 00:24:00,858
Let's go back to the fire,
you're probably exhausted.

238
00:24:13,245 --> 00:24:14,413
Just talk to him.

239
00:24:14,580 --> 00:24:15,789
All right.

240
00:24:20,753 --> 00:24:21,962
Uh, excuse me, sir?

241
00:24:22,129 --> 00:24:23,380
I didn't want to intrude,

242
00:24:23,547 --> 00:24:25,883
but I just had to say
that I'm such an admirer of yours.

243
00:24:26,133 --> 00:24:28,719
<i>Your foundation
literally saved my sister's--</i>

244
00:24:28,886 --> 00:24:31,472
One more word and I'll cut your throat.
You understand?

245
00:24:33,766 --> 00:24:35,934
This is my fucking vacation.

246
00:24:47,905 --> 00:24:51,617
Apparently, whatever they're looking for
is in the Ojal prison.

247
00:24:52,618 --> 00:24:56,914
These lunatics plan to steal a cannon
from a Union cavalry unit.

248
00:24:57,081 --> 00:24:58,415
Blast their way in.

249
00:25:00,584 --> 00:25:04,088
I don't have time
for color-by-numbers bullshit.

250
00:25:10,427 --> 00:25:11,929
I'll ride at dawn.

251
00:25:12,429 --> 00:25:13,847
I'll go get whatever you want

252
00:25:14,014 --> 00:25:16,266
out of that prison
and bring it back myself.

253
00:25:17,142 --> 00:25:19,478
Suppose you make it out alive.
What's your price?

254
00:25:20,270 --> 00:25:21,772
Nothing but a few words.

255
00:25:22,773 --> 00:25:25,025
I want the story behind your tattoo.

256
00:25:26,443 --> 00:25:28,112
What's your interest in it?

257
00:25:29,697 --> 00:25:32,533
You ever heard of a man named Arnold?

258
00:25:33,283 --> 00:25:36,537
You could say he was
the original settler of these parts.

259
00:25:36,954 --> 00:25:42,209
He created a world where you could
do anything you want except one thing.

260
00:25:43,043 --> 00:25:44,628
You can't die.

261
00:25:45,379 --> 00:25:48,465
Which means
no matter how real this world seems,

262
00:25:48,632 --> 00:25:50,467
it is still just a game.

263
00:25:51,218 --> 00:25:54,513
But then
Arnold went and broke his own rule.

264
00:25:55,305 --> 00:25:58,308
He died right here in the park.

265
00:25:59,977 --> 00:26:03,188
Except I believe
he had one story left to tell.

266
00:26:06,483 --> 00:26:10,988
A story with real stakes, real violence.

267
00:26:12,197 --> 00:26:15,075
You could say
I'm here to honor his legacy.

268
00:26:16,326 --> 00:26:19,329
<i>And I think your tattoo
is the next piece of the puzzle.</i>

269
00:26:21,498 --> 00:26:23,917
So, do we have a wager?

270
00:26:25,002 --> 00:26:29,006
You aim to break into a prison
and take out 20 men alone?

271
00:26:29,173 --> 00:26:32,509
Not alone. I'll take Lawrence here.

272
00:26:33,927 --> 00:26:35,554
And I'll need one match.

273
00:26:36,180 --> 00:26:37,931
One match,

274
00:26:38,098 --> 00:26:42,186
one pistol and one idiot.

275
00:26:45,856 --> 00:26:47,357
I'll take those odds.

276
00:27:08,754 --> 00:27:11,423
You gonna give me the silent treatment
the whole way there?

277
00:27:12,049 --> 00:27:14,384
<i>You should've left me hanging
from those gallows.</i>

278
00:27:14,551 --> 00:27:18,889
Least I could've died in peace
without having to hear you yammer.

279
00:27:28,440 --> 00:27:30,150
Don't suppose you have a light?

280
00:27:30,400 --> 00:27:31,568
No smoking in here.

281
00:27:31,735 --> 00:27:33,487
<i>Normally, I'm sure,</i>

282
00:27:33,654 --> 00:27:36,573
but this is the finest tobacco
a man can enjoy.

283
00:27:37,407 --> 00:27:41,119
Hand-rolled on the ample thighs
of exotic women.

284
00:27:41,912 --> 00:27:44,164
<i>Perhaps you'd like to try one yourself.</i>

285
00:27:57,761 --> 00:27:59,596
Choices, Lawrence.

286
00:28:00,264 --> 00:28:02,933
You know, you tell yourself
you've been at the mercy of mine

287
00:28:03,100 --> 00:28:05,602
because it spares you
consideration of your own.

288
00:28:05,811 --> 00:28:08,313
Because if you did
consider your choices,

289
00:28:08,480 --> 00:28:11,441
you'd be confronted with a truth
you could not comprehend.

290
00:28:12,276 --> 00:28:15,362
That no choice you
ever made was your own.

291
00:28:16,446 --> 00:28:18,866
You have always been a prisoner.

292
00:28:22,786 --> 00:28:26,790
What if I told you
I'm here to set you free?

293
00:28:51,064 --> 00:28:52,316
Let's go!

294
00:28:56,486 --> 00:28:57,654
Horse thieves.

295
00:28:57,821 --> 00:29:00,824
Damn fools shot up a couple of pokes
practically in front of us.

296
00:29:00,991 --> 00:29:03,702
Well, the only fool I see is the
one standing right in front of me.

297
00:29:04,494 --> 00:29:08,999
Deputy, you have there in your custody
the most wanted man in three territories.

298
00:29:10,542 --> 00:29:15,505
<i>Lawrence Pedro Maria Gonzalez.</i>

299
00:29:16,840 --> 00:29:17,925
Yeah.

300
00:29:19,509 --> 00:29:20,844
Heard you slipped the rope.

301
00:29:21,553 --> 00:29:23,221
<i>Dropped some damn good men in exchange.</i>

302
00:29:23,388 --> 00:29:27,017
The way he tells it,
he's more partial to a firing squad.

303
00:29:27,559 --> 00:29:29,436
<i>I reckon we'll be happy to oblige.</i>

304
00:29:39,196 --> 00:29:41,198
I'm gonna fucking kill you.

305
00:29:43,200 --> 00:29:44,868
Maybe someday.

306
00:29:46,536 --> 00:29:48,455
Lock him up with the other man.

307
00:29:56,213 --> 00:29:57,547
Enjoy the cigars.

308
00:29:57,756 --> 00:29:59,841
Go fuck yourself.

309
00:30:02,761 --> 00:30:04,429
<i>And just who are you supposed to be?</i>

310
00:30:06,390 --> 00:30:07,724
Your salvation.

311
00:30:36,253 --> 00:30:38,338
<i>I don't believe we've ever met.</i>

312
00:30:38,505 --> 00:30:41,174
No, we haven't.

313
00:30:42,426 --> 00:30:47,973
You know, you always seemed like
a market-tested kind of thing.

314
00:30:49,182 --> 00:30:52,144
Big gun, tasteful scar.

315
00:30:53,311 --> 00:30:57,983
Locked in your little cycle
like a prized poodle after its own tail.

316
00:30:58,150 --> 00:31:02,154
You sound like a man who's grown tired
of wearing his guts on the inside.

317
00:31:02,320 --> 00:31:07,451
There's no need to get testy.
I'm just curious about your worldview.

318
00:31:08,744 --> 00:31:11,163
Some kind of half-native mumbo jumbo?

319
00:31:11,371 --> 00:31:12,372
<i>It's simple.</i>

320
00:31:12,873 --> 00:31:15,042
I believe that only the truly brave

321
00:31:15,208 --> 00:31:18,045
can look at the world
and understand that all of it,

322
00:31:19,671 --> 00:31:23,133
gods, men, everything else,

323
00:31:23,300 --> 00:31:24,968
<i>will end badly.</i>

324
00:31:26,678 --> 00:31:28,472
No one will be saved.

325
00:31:29,639 --> 00:31:31,975
Maybe we've got more in common
than I thought.

326
00:31:32,476 --> 00:31:35,979
What about you? What turns
of fate have brought you here?

327
00:31:36,146 --> 00:31:40,525
It's a long story,
and we don't have the time.

328
00:31:40,692 --> 00:31:43,403
Got more time than your friend, sadly.

329
00:31:43,653 --> 00:31:46,364
<i>It will be a few more days
before my friends show up.</i>

330
00:31:46,573 --> 00:31:48,658
Three days. Normally.

331
00:31:48,825 --> 00:31:52,746
I'm afraid I don't have time for that,
so we're leaving now.

332
00:31:58,710 --> 00:32:00,462
I've got a request for
a pyrotechnic effect.

333
00:32:00,712 --> 00:32:03,840
<i>Los Diablos. Low-yield, two charges.</i>

334
00:32:07,010 --> 00:32:08,095
Approved.

335
00:32:08,261 --> 00:32:09,554
Authorizing.

336
00:32:32,619 --> 00:32:34,204
Step lively, Hector.

337
00:32:49,761 --> 00:32:52,264
- Any last words?
- Get it over with.

338
00:33:30,468 --> 00:33:32,470
Motherfucker.

339
00:33:42,272 --> 00:33:43,607
One match.

340
00:33:43,982 --> 00:33:45,775
You're a capable man.

341
00:33:46,526 --> 00:33:48,695
We could do with your help
where we're going.

342
00:33:48,862 --> 00:33:51,281
- Afraid not.
- We owe you a debt.

343
00:33:51,656 --> 00:33:54,951
No, your friend here
simply owes me a word or two.

344
00:33:55,452 --> 00:33:58,788
<i>That'd do. And a word of advice.</i>

345
00:33:59,164 --> 00:34:03,710
That thing you're looking for?
You're never gonna find it in that safe.

346
00:34:20,685 --> 00:34:23,313
I was seven when they rode into my town.

347
00:34:24,189 --> 00:34:26,399
Masked men in devils' horns.

348
00:34:26,816 --> 00:34:30,487
They killed everyone.
Women, children, even the animals.

349
00:34:34,324 --> 00:34:37,160
They gutted my mother from her jaw
to her sex.

350
00:34:37,994 --> 00:34:40,997
<i>I had to paint her
warm blood over my skin</i>

351
00:34:41,164 --> 00:34:43,750
<i>to make sure that they would think
I was dead.</i>

352
00:34:44,209 --> 00:34:48,338
Every one of them I tracked down, I
used their blood to paint my skin again.

353
00:34:50,757 --> 00:34:52,342
Only one man left.

354
00:34:54,052 --> 00:34:55,679
The head of the snake.

355
00:34:58,932 --> 00:35:00,183
What's his name?

356
00:35:02,686 --> 00:35:04,229
He has many names.

357
00:35:06,189 --> 00:35:08,358
Most know him as Wyatt.

358
00:36:08,168 --> 00:36:12,589
Hey, little girl, what is this?
What does it mean?

359
00:36:12,756 --> 00:36:14,382
Don't waste your breath, lady.

360
00:36:14,549 --> 00:36:17,177
That thing's
part of their so-called religion.

361
00:36:17,969 --> 00:36:20,680
Ain't none of them's gonna tell you
nothing about that.

362
00:36:28,730 --> 00:36:33,068
It's $5 for an hour.
$4 if you bathe first.

363
00:36:33,568 --> 00:36:35,945
Well, if we just get the one,

364
00:36:36,112 --> 00:36:39,616
do I get a discount
for being second and all?

365
00:36:39,783 --> 00:36:41,868
I'm sure we can work something out.

366
00:36:43,036 --> 00:36:44,287
Come on.

367
00:36:56,383 --> 00:37:01,429
The tall one, I've seen him before,
hanging in the window of the post office.

368
00:37:01,638 --> 00:37:04,057
Bandits? Do you think
they're here for something?

369
00:37:04,265 --> 00:37:07,519
I think they're interested in
more than a turn at Franny's backside.

370
00:37:09,270 --> 00:37:11,106
I think he rides with Hector.

371
00:37:11,272 --> 00:37:14,067
Is that the one
they say lives out with the savages?

372
00:37:18,947 --> 00:37:20,532
That's the one.

373
00:37:30,291 --> 00:37:31,584
<i>Taking off? I just got here.</i>

374
00:37:31,751 --> 00:37:33,378
You gave me what I needed.

375
00:37:34,295 --> 00:37:39,092
So, is that all I'm good for?
Letting off a little stress?

376
00:37:39,259 --> 00:37:40,802
Who says I'm stressed?

377
00:37:41,386 --> 00:37:42,971
You have your tells.

378
00:37:46,224 --> 00:37:50,019
Oh, yes, Bernard, master of observation.

379
00:37:58,987 --> 00:38:00,864
Tomorrow, I have to talk to Ford.

380
00:38:01,364 --> 00:38:02,532
Why?

381
00:38:02,699 --> 00:38:04,951
He's creating chaos in the park.

382
00:38:05,243 --> 00:38:07,662
And the board will be descending
at any moment.

383
00:38:08,455 --> 00:38:10,290
I need to buy some time.

384
00:38:10,457 --> 00:38:11,458
Some advice?

385
00:38:13,001 --> 00:38:15,545
Best to not show him
you're nervous or defensive.

386
00:38:16,254 --> 00:38:18,631
I have nothing to be defensive about.

387
00:38:19,007 --> 00:38:20,675
Then don't cross your arms.

388
00:38:21,468 --> 00:38:23,052
It's an ancient instinct.

389
00:38:23,553 --> 00:38:26,139
The belly is the most vulnerable part
of every animal.

390
00:38:28,141 --> 00:38:31,269
It's so sexy
being compared to a frightened beast.

391
00:38:32,645 --> 00:38:33,897
There.

392
00:38:34,772 --> 00:38:36,774
That's the posture you're looking for.

393
00:38:44,032 --> 00:38:47,827
Sometimes, despite your best efforts,

394
00:38:48,995 --> 00:38:51,706
you can actually be quite charming.

395
00:39:05,595 --> 00:39:07,305
Have the neighbors complained?

396
00:39:07,889 --> 00:39:10,266
Safe to say, they're asking questions.

397
00:39:10,808 --> 00:39:15,522
The rocks would prefer not to move,
but we shall move them yet.

398
00:39:18,316 --> 00:39:20,485
Perhaps I can help you with that.

399
00:39:21,653 --> 00:39:24,697
The narrative you're creating
is clearly a massive endeavor.

400
00:39:24,989 --> 00:39:26,366
<i>If you need more time,</i>

401
00:39:26,533 --> 00:39:28,701
<i>I'm sure the board would be
happy to oblige.</i>

402
00:39:28,868 --> 00:39:31,913
I'm sure they'd be happier
for me to delay it indefinitely.

403
00:39:35,124 --> 00:39:36,501
Come with me.

404
00:39:47,053 --> 00:39:52,141
You imagine I have gone mad, do you?
Lost my way?

405
00:39:52,308 --> 00:39:56,437
We're simply concerned about
the extent of the changes you're making.

406
00:39:56,813 --> 00:39:58,481
We want to protect your legacy.

407
00:39:59,315 --> 00:40:00,650
My legacy?

408
00:40:06,739 --> 00:40:08,658
You don't like this place very much,
do you?

409
00:40:09,909 --> 00:40:12,203
I've seen many of you
come and go over the years,

410
00:40:12,370 --> 00:40:15,290
and I can tell the ones
who enjoy their time here

411
00:40:15,456 --> 00:40:17,000
and the ones who don't.

412
00:40:17,750 --> 00:40:21,546
I admire it, the audacity of it.

413
00:40:22,338 --> 00:40:24,924
I'd forgotten how beautiful it is.

414
00:40:25,091 --> 00:40:28,011
I came here once as a child
with my parents.

415
00:40:28,219 --> 00:40:32,932
I think we even sat at this table.
Or maybe that one.

416
00:40:39,564 --> 00:40:41,024
When I started working here,

417
00:40:41,190 --> 00:40:44,485
I realized this place wasn't something
I would enjoy.

418
00:40:49,365 --> 00:40:50,450
In the beginning,

419
00:40:50,617 --> 00:40:53,995
I imagined
things would be perfectly balanced.

420
00:40:55,246 --> 00:40:58,833
Even had a bet with my partner, Arnold,
to that effect.

421
00:40:59,250 --> 00:41:00,710
We made 100 hopeful storylines.

422
00:41:00,877 --> 00:41:03,087
Of course,
almost no one took us up on them.

423
00:41:03,796 --> 00:41:05,340
I lost the bet.

424
00:41:06,299 --> 00:41:10,470
Arnold always held
a somewhat dim view of people.

425
00:41:10,762 --> 00:41:12,513
He preferred the hosts.

426
00:41:12,680 --> 00:41:16,017
He begged me to not let you people in,
the moneymen.

427
00:41:16,517 --> 00:41:17,727
<i>Delos.</i>

428
00:41:17,894 --> 00:41:19,437
<i>But I told him we'd be fine,</i>

429
00:41:19,604 --> 00:41:21,939
that you didn't understand
what you were paying for.

430
00:41:22,106 --> 00:41:27,320
It's not a business venture,
not a theme park, but an entire world.

431
00:41:29,030 --> 00:41:30,323
<i>We designed every inch of it.</i>

432
00:41:33,701 --> 00:41:35,286
Every blade of grass.

433
00:41:43,211 --> 00:41:45,004
In here, we were gods.

434
00:41:46,005 --> 00:41:49,634
And you were merely our guests.

435
00:42:09,112 --> 00:42:10,988
And how did that work out for Arnold?

436
00:42:12,031 --> 00:42:15,243
Sadly, he lost his perspective.

437
00:42:15,785 --> 00:42:17,203
He went mad.

438
00:42:18,621 --> 00:42:20,832
I haven't, as you well know.

439
00:42:20,998 --> 00:42:24,043
I have always seen things

440
00:42:24,961 --> 00:42:26,295
very clearly.

441
00:42:31,884 --> 00:42:34,846
This is the table I sat at
with my parents.

442
00:42:37,640 --> 00:42:39,767
This is the chair I sat in.

443
00:42:41,811 --> 00:42:43,980
We know everything about our guests,
don't we?

444
00:42:44,147 --> 00:42:46,691
As we know everything
about our employees.

445
00:42:49,652 --> 00:42:52,780
I do hope
you will be careful with Bernard.

446
00:42:55,825 --> 00:42:58,995
He has a sensitive disposition.

447
00:43:01,748 --> 00:43:04,625
I beg your pardon, <i>señorita.</i>

448
00:43:12,675 --> 00:43:15,386
<i>There have been
many of you over the years,</i>

449
00:43:15,553 --> 00:43:16,637
<i>and we have always...</i>

450
00:43:17,221 --> 00:43:19,682
Almost always,
found a way to make it work.

451
00:43:20,725 --> 00:43:24,145
So, I will ask you nicely.

452
00:43:25,646 --> 00:43:29,567
Please don't get in my way.

453
00:43:44,916 --> 00:43:46,834
The board will agree with me.

454
00:43:47,543 --> 00:43:49,295
They'll be sending a representative.

455
00:43:50,004 --> 00:43:52,840
But they already have.
I thought they would've told you.

456
00:43:55,760 --> 00:44:00,681
That won't be necessary, Manu.
Not anymore. You can join the others.

457
00:44:17,573 --> 00:44:21,327
You can tell the board that my narrative
will be completed on time,

458
00:44:21,494 --> 00:44:27,166
and it won't be a retrospective,
as I'm sure you have all feared.

459
00:44:35,466 --> 00:44:37,510
I'm not the sentimental type.

460
00:44:48,104 --> 00:44:51,274
Holden says
this Slim's got a whole gang with him.

461
00:44:52,024 --> 00:44:53,943
So, I need you to stay here.

462
00:44:54,527 --> 00:44:57,256
If you're outnumbered, the last thing
you need is somebody standing by.

463
00:44:57,280 --> 00:44:59,574
- I can help.
- No. No, no, no.

464
00:45:01,367 --> 00:45:02,761
Um, I know it doesn't make
any sense to you,

465
00:45:02,785 --> 00:45:04,620
but I can't get hurt in there,
but you can.

466
00:45:05,079 --> 00:45:06,622
I would hate to see that happen.

467
00:45:06,789 --> 00:45:10,334
Just stay here. Okay? Be safe.

468
00:45:21,012 --> 00:45:23,973
- Aw. Did you get a goodbye kiss?
- Shut up.

469
00:45:24,140 --> 00:45:27,435
Seriously, if you don't bang her
by tomorrow, I'm calling dibs.

470
00:45:27,602 --> 00:45:30,104
Okay, listen up.
It's gonna be a bag of nails in there.

471
00:45:30,271 --> 00:45:32,273
Slim and his boys got us outnumbered.

472
00:45:32,899 --> 00:45:36,861
On top of that, there's a family
runs this place. Good people.

473
00:45:37,361 --> 00:45:40,132
We need to make sure that snake-hearted
son of a bitch doesn't try to--

474
00:45:40,156 --> 00:45:42,450
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Risk, reward. We get it.

475
00:45:42,617 --> 00:45:45,161
Come on. Let's go fuck these fuckers up.

476
00:45:48,664 --> 00:45:51,000
The fuck is that? Huh?

477
00:45:52,168 --> 00:45:54,921
- I look like a dog to you? Huh?
- No, sir.

478
00:45:56,130 --> 00:45:57,924
Feed that to them.

479
00:46:01,886 --> 00:46:03,137
Slap leather, cocksuckers.

480
00:46:03,638 --> 00:46:04,680
Oh, God!

481
00:46:31,040 --> 00:46:32,875
Did I fucking tell you, or what?

482
00:47:07,785 --> 00:47:09,829
Upgrade. Nice.

483
00:47:13,249 --> 00:47:16,877
Ain't normally the type
to complain, but this is just foolhardy.

484
00:47:17,086 --> 00:47:18,879
Two men taking on Wyatt.

485
00:47:19,422 --> 00:47:22,425
Keep talking, and I'm gonna
take the horse back, Lawrence.

486
00:47:22,758 --> 00:47:27,304
Wyatt's freaks just wiped out the
last group that went seeking him out.

487
00:47:28,055 --> 00:47:30,808
And here we are riding right after him.

488
00:47:34,353 --> 00:47:36,605
I'm just trying to convince you

489
00:47:36,772 --> 00:47:40,109
not to get yourself,
and me as a bystander, killed.

490
00:47:40,526 --> 00:47:43,487
I'm not gonna get myself killed.

491
00:47:44,280 --> 00:47:46,615
Don't think I didn't notice
that distinction.

492
00:48:07,386 --> 00:48:10,723
Looks like Wyatt's men
left somebody behind after all.

493
00:48:13,601 --> 00:48:14,769
It's Teddy.

494
00:48:16,562 --> 00:48:18,230
I should've guessed.

495
00:48:19,148 --> 00:48:21,609
Please, put me out of my misery.

496
00:48:22,985 --> 00:48:24,570
I'm sorry, Teddy.

497
00:48:27,073 --> 00:48:28,783
It looks like misery's all you got.

498
00:48:32,620 --> 00:48:34,330
<i>Let me out of this, God damn it!</i>

499
00:48:34,538 --> 00:48:36,332
That reward is dead or alive, right?

500
00:48:36,665 --> 00:48:38,501
Always best to bring 'em in alive.

501
00:48:38,751 --> 00:48:40,294
Can we at least gag him?

502
00:48:40,836 --> 00:48:42,296
That's a fine idea.

503
00:48:47,802 --> 00:48:49,011
<i>Aw, come on.</i>

504
00:48:49,178 --> 00:48:51,778
Look, I know you're in it for the money.
You ain't no real lawman.

505
00:48:52,348 --> 00:48:55,392
- Shut up, you.
- Look, my boss, El Lazo,

506
00:48:55,559 --> 00:48:59,980
he'll pay you twice what the marshals will
if you cut me loose and get me to Pariah.

507
00:49:00,147 --> 00:49:02,358
- Listen to me, you lowdown piece of dirt.
- Hey--

508
00:49:02,525 --> 00:49:03,859
These men won't--

509
00:49:07,446 --> 00:49:09,365
- What the fuck?
<i>- Relax, man.</i>

510
00:49:09,949 --> 00:49:12,451
You have no idea how lucky we just got.

511
00:49:12,618 --> 00:49:14,245
Lucky? You just shot an innocent man!

512
00:49:14,411 --> 00:49:17,456
No, he is a robot, just like her,
and just like Slim here,

513
00:49:17,623 --> 00:49:20,167
except that Slim works for El Lazo,

514
00:49:20,334 --> 00:49:24,213
and El Lazo is our ticket
to the best ride in the park.

515
00:49:24,380 --> 00:49:27,216
Your bullshit mission
led us right to an Easter egg.

516
00:49:30,803 --> 00:49:32,263
You're not going to let him go.

517
00:49:32,429 --> 00:49:34,223
Well, well. Look at you.

518
00:49:35,224 --> 00:49:37,685
You're starting to grow on me,
farm girl. Now, out of the way.

519
00:49:40,521 --> 00:49:41,814
Don't you dare.

520
00:49:42,022 --> 00:49:45,651
See? This is gonna be fun!
Now we're each gonna have one.

521
00:49:45,818 --> 00:49:47,736
I won't fuck mine either.

522
00:49:47,903 --> 00:49:49,071
You're disgusting.

523
00:49:49,238 --> 00:49:50,489
Just an acquired taste.

524
00:49:50,656 --> 00:49:52,256
You're gonna grow to love me, I promise.

525
00:49:55,286 --> 00:49:56,537
Come on. Hmm?

526
00:49:58,998 --> 00:50:00,249
Come on.

527
00:50:00,958 --> 00:50:02,751
Go black hat with me.

528
00:50:03,586 --> 00:50:06,088
Come on.
You got to, you know, save the girl.

529
00:50:06,255 --> 00:50:07,590
Now give me a little something.

530
00:50:07,756 --> 00:50:09,758
What is your problem?
The second we get away

531
00:50:09,925 --> 00:50:11,845
from the real world,
you turn into an evil prick.

532
00:50:12,428 --> 00:50:13,846
Evil?

533
00:50:14,263 --> 00:50:15,931
It's a fucking game, Billy!

534
00:50:16,098 --> 00:50:19,059
<i>- Don't call me Billy!
- Are you still trying to impress her?</i>

535
00:50:19,226 --> 00:50:22,146
Because I guarantee she does not give
a shit about how you play this game.

536
00:50:22,271 --> 00:50:24,607
<i>- Do you, Dolores?</i>
- What's he talking about, William?

537
00:50:25,191 --> 00:50:28,611
She will be just fine
with a trip down the dark side.

538
00:50:29,111 --> 00:50:30,696
And so will you.

539
00:50:34,283 --> 00:50:35,618
Trust me.

540
00:50:42,875 --> 00:50:45,794
So, which way to Pariah?

541
00:50:46,629 --> 00:50:49,131
Aw, you just let me take it from here.

542
00:50:54,595 --> 00:50:56,305
All right, time for the floor show.

543
00:50:57,097 --> 00:50:59,475
Got some guests
riding with Hector this time.

544
00:51:19,828 --> 00:51:21,997
Let's give them something to shoot at.

545
00:51:22,623 --> 00:51:24,458
Re-task a few of those soldiers.

546
00:51:26,126 --> 00:51:29,129
If you're riding into our town
under the company of armed men,

547
00:51:29,296 --> 00:51:31,298
<i>you'll need to state your business.</i>

548
00:51:31,966 --> 00:51:33,175
Mayhem.

549
00:52:15,759 --> 00:52:19,763
Well, hello there. I want to talk.

550
00:52:19,930 --> 00:52:22,182
Interesting way
of starting a conversation.

551
00:52:23,100 --> 00:52:25,436
Oh, it's an interesting kind of day.

552
00:52:34,820 --> 00:52:36,572
Now, my lovely friend,

553
00:52:38,073 --> 00:52:40,034
what deal is it you want to make?

554
00:52:40,826 --> 00:52:42,661
You're here for what's in the safe.

555
00:52:43,537 --> 00:52:44,657
And how would you know that?

556
00:52:45,080 --> 00:52:48,917
I can always tell when a man wants
something that's not on the menu.

557
00:52:50,586 --> 00:52:54,423
I'll give you the combination
in exchange for some answers.

558
00:52:54,590 --> 00:52:56,300
<i>You assume I have any answers.</i>

559
00:52:58,719 --> 00:53:01,305
This world is madness.

560
00:53:02,973 --> 00:53:05,017
I want to know about this.

561
00:53:07,102 --> 00:53:08,228
I've got a couple families

562
00:53:08,395 --> 00:53:10,155
in the homestead
who changed their itinerary.

563
00:53:10,272 --> 00:53:11,940
They're headed into town.

564
00:53:12,107 --> 00:53:15,736
<i>Should be there in 20 minutes or so.
Place is a bloodbath.</i>

565
00:53:15,903 --> 00:53:20,574
Fine. Cut these guys off. Jam their
weapons and send in the cavalry.

566
00:53:28,874 --> 00:53:30,626
Oh, shit.

567
00:53:33,921 --> 00:53:37,007
We'll give them a night in lockup, then
have one of the girls at the Mariposa

568
00:53:37,174 --> 00:53:38,854
bring them a key
hidden in their breakfast.

569
00:53:39,009 --> 00:53:41,470
If the guests are squared away,
let's wrap it up.

570
00:53:42,638 --> 00:53:44,640
This is a shade.

571
00:53:46,100 --> 00:53:49,728
Sacred native lore.
They make figures of 'em.

572
00:53:52,356 --> 00:53:53,649
Sixty.

573
00:54:01,949 --> 00:54:03,700
And what does this shade do?

574
00:54:04,910 --> 00:54:06,078
You've seen this?

575
00:54:06,620 --> 00:54:07,788
What is it?

576
00:54:08,414 --> 00:54:10,374
<i>The man who walks between worlds.</i>

577
00:54:11,083 --> 00:54:14,128
They were sent from hell
to oversee our world.

578
00:54:17,256 --> 00:54:18,257
Forty-seven.

579
00:54:31,979 --> 00:54:34,314
Is this the last thing
you required of me?

580
00:54:35,357 --> 00:54:38,527
'Cause we need a little more time
than the constabulary will allow.

581
00:54:38,694 --> 00:54:40,630
Sweetheart, if I took
that manner of interest in you,

582
00:54:40,654 --> 00:54:42,865
you'd have no say
in how long we'd need whatsoever.

583
00:54:48,954 --> 00:54:50,456
I thought I was crazy,

584
00:54:51,957 --> 00:54:55,252
but I got shot here.

585
00:54:57,921 --> 00:54:59,506
- There's no wound.
- No.

586
00:54:59,673 --> 00:55:00,841
But I was shot.

587
00:55:01,842 --> 00:55:05,387
And this was standing over me.
And then it was as if it never happened.

588
00:55:06,263 --> 00:55:09,725
I want you to cut me right there.

589
00:55:27,701 --> 00:55:30,370
I'm not in the habit
of cutting into defenseless women.

590
00:55:31,079 --> 00:55:32,956
Some big, bad outlaw.

591
00:55:33,123 --> 00:55:35,876
The Dreamwalker said there were some
who could see them.

592
00:55:38,212 --> 00:55:40,422
- That it's a blessing from God.
- A blessing?

593
00:55:40,589 --> 00:55:42,966
To see the masters
who pull your strings.

594
00:55:48,138 --> 00:55:50,224
They don't know
what they're talking about.

595
00:55:58,106 --> 00:56:02,569
You wanna die lying down
or up on your feet?

596
00:56:03,862 --> 00:56:04,863
Go to hell.

597
00:56:24,258 --> 00:56:25,425
Go on, then.

598
00:56:27,302 --> 00:56:29,054
This would be the first goddamn time

599
00:56:29,221 --> 00:56:31,221
I've had to ask a man
to put his hands on me twice.

600
00:56:56,915 --> 00:56:59,668
<i>Open up, Escaton, or we'll fire!</i>

601
00:57:00,877 --> 00:57:02,337
What does it mean?

602
00:57:03,755 --> 00:57:05,048
That I'm not crazy after all.

603
00:57:05,215 --> 00:57:07,009
<i>Last chance, Escaton!</i>

604
00:57:07,384 --> 00:57:09,344
<i>Come out or we're shooting!</i>

605
00:57:12,806 --> 00:57:14,725
And that none of this matters.

